<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">The present species was described after a specimen from East Africa; the type (no. 183/47) is still present in the Collection.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Berlese compares the species with 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">magnus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anomalus">anomalus</taxonomicName>
and in general shape it reminds indeed of these species. The notogastral hairs are, however, very small, hardly visible, slightly pointing backwards, and irregularly curved. The type-specimen is closed (as Berlese mentioned already); the colour is dark-brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
